{"cursor":"19889","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"The 'Viable Systems Model', or 'VSM' is a model of the organisational structure\nof any viable or autonomous system. A viable system is any system organised in\nsuch a way as to meet the demands of surviving in the changing environment. One\nof the prime features of systems that survive is that they are adaptable. The\nVSM expresses a model for a viable system, which is an abstracted cybernetic\n(regulation theory) description that is applicable to any organisation that is a\nviable system and capable of autonomy.\n","linknr":210,"url":"Viable_system_model","recorded":1362677167,"links":20,"instances":["cybernetics","telecommunication","abstract"],"pdf":["http://www.futurovenezuela.org/_curso/6-sysmeth.pdf","http://www.fractal-consulting.com/VSM-Intro-Fractal.pdf","http://www.tetradian.com/download/togaf_ea-soe_apr08_FV.pdf","http://www.moderntimesworkplace.com/good_reading/GRRespSelf/TheViableSystemModel.pdf"],"categories":["Cybernetics","Cognitive science literature","Systems theory"],"headings":["Overview","Components of the Viable System Model","Rules for the viable system","Measuring performance","Metalanguage","Applying VSM","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Vsm.gif/320px-Vsm.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Performance.png/500px-Performance.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Beer_Metalnaguage.PNG/150px-Beer_Metalnaguage.PNG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki